      "side": 1,
      "message": "\" I like that we propagate errors upward through steps in the same way that we propagate them in normal Go programs \"\n\nI agree, which is why I dislike defer td.FinishStep(ctx, \u0026err), or defer s.Done(\u0026err) as it was named in the last\niteration.\n\n\nI think FinishStep and Done are trying to do too much, both recording the sub-step we\u0027re at and also error reporting.\n\nThe code would be much simpler if recording steps was one process and returning errors just followed normal Go flow, i.e.:\n\nfunc someStep() error {\n  defer td.StartStep(\"Foo\").Done()\n\n  return nil\n}\n\nAnd count on calls to sklog.Errorf() to record errors.\n\nIf that\u0027s the way it worked then I\u0027d be fine with checking error responses from Do().",
